<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Federal Blood Ouantum Laws. Tribal Sovereignty and Individual Rights</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>INTRODUCTION</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The United States government first used blood quantum (or degree of Indian blood) as a criteriafor determining “Indian-ness” in the General Allotment Act of 1887. The effect of that and othersubsequent policies based on degree of Indian blood has been to disenfranchize many members of the American Indian community. Differential treatment by the federal government towards Indians based upon blood quantum criteria has created rifts within Indian communities. <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Issues such as pedigree, lineage, federal recognition, certification, and identification numbers have emerged only in the last 113 years.</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Today,American Indians are the only group of people in the United States who have to prove their heritage.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->This government policy merits question beyond purely social ramifications. <br>
<br>
As quasi-sovereignnation-states, American Indian nations should have the right to define their own citizenship as they see fit.The federal government created the blood-quantum policy as a tool to infringe upon tribal sovereignty inorder to pursue their own gains.<br>
<br>
The United States government has obligations to American Indian nations (and their citizens) as aresult of treaty agreements. There is no mention made of blood quantum or degree of Indian blood in any of these treaties. The use of blood quantum standards is one of many methods employed by the United States government in an attempt to renege on their treaty obligations. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The desired affect of blood-quantum policy is “statistical extermination”’ of American Indians.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">If there are no Indians and no Indian nations left that the government chooses to recognize, then they are freed from their treaty obligations.</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>OBJECTIVE</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The objective of this research is to explore the socio-legal consequences of blood quantum policy.How do blood quantum requirements affect the American Indian community? Firstly, on a national level,how does this policy affect tribal sovereignty? Secondly, on a societal basis, how has this policy divided the American Indian community? Lastly, how has blood quantum criteria affected individuals of mixed racial heritage? How does this policy interfere with their right to their own identity?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>PERSONAL STATEMENT</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Being of mixed blood myself, with ancestors from the Cherokee, Lenape, and Oglaia Lakota nations, I plan to pursue a career in American Indian law. Last year I decided that I would like to do research on tribal sovereignty. After researching several different aspects of sovereignty I have decided to focus my studies on the issue of blood quantum and federal Indian race law. Being of mixed ancestry, it is asubject that I am passionate about, and have great interest in.In my initial research I have uncovered a sizeable amount of information on the subjects of racial identity, “indian-ness”, mixed-bloods, and the recent influx of people who choose to identify themselves as American Indian.<br>
<br>
M. Annette Jaimes (whose work I cite in this proposal) wrote about federal Indian identification policy in 1992. I would like to expand on her research and also include the personal accounts of different members of the American Indian community in order to explore the social impacts of the law.I feel that that this experience will benefit me throughout my career, both in terms of the research experience itself, and the information that I will gain access to. This is directly related to my career choice and I am very excited to have the opportunity to do research on this topic.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>OUTLINE</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
Initially, I would like to look at how blood quantum policy was first implemented and how it has evolved. What was the legal basis for the creation of such a policy, and what was the socio-political moodof the era? To do this I will examine the law within a historical framework. How does American Indian race law compare to other U.S. policies of the era, including Jim Crow laws, and other policies aimed atAmerican Indian populations? <br>
<br>
I will also compare the U.S.-tribal government relationship to other nation-to-nation relationships. Then I will explore and compare official federal, state, and tribal definitions of “Indian-ness”, and contrast that to individual perspectives of what an “indian” is. <br>
<br>
Secondly, I will examine American Indian society and tribal governments. Historically, how have mixed-bloods been received in the American Indian community? How has the perception and importance of mixed-blood evolved? How have these aspects interacted with federal Indian law to influence tribal government policies regarding people of mixed heritage? What do the tribal leaders feel are the results of blood quantum laws and what do they see for the future if the current laws do not change? If their sovereignty were respected, how would their governments deal with people of mixed blood? <br>
<br>
Finally, I will conduct interviews to ascertain how this policy affects American Indians on an individual basis. How do mixed-bloods of American Indian descent identify themselves? How are they accepted within the American Indian community and larger society? How has federal law affected therelationship between full-bloods and mixed-bloods within the American Indian community? What has been their personal experience with federal blood quantum laws? In what ways do they feel that blood quantum laws are detrimental to community cohesion7 How do full-bloods regard blood quantum laws and mixed-bloods?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>METHODS AND GOALS</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1) The first portion of my research will be devoted to data-gathering and literature review. I will draw upon journals, magazine articles, and books written from both the American Indian and majority perspective.<br>
2) I will interview approximately 15 tribal leaders and government officials regarding blood quantum policies. Most of these interviews will take place within the Southern California area or over the phone, but some will take place in the Mid-West and the South in order to ensure a good balance of representation among Indian nations, whose governments and cultures vary greatly.<br>
3) I will conduct interviews with approximately 30 American Indians of mixed racial descent in order to gain some perspective on their experiences as mixed-blood individuals.Most of these will again take place in Southern California, but some will take place in the Mid-West and the South. I will also interview some full-blooded Indians regarding theirviews of mixed-bloods and the blood quantum issue.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>STUDENT RESPONSIBLITIES</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
My responsibility is to conduct a thorough search of available literature regarding blood quantumlaw, review its history, and critique it. Rather than rely only on written accounts that sometimes do not accurately represent the American Indian perspective, it is important that I supplement this academic review with interviews of people who are directly affected by Indian race law. (i.e. tribal leaders, and people within the American Indian community). Upon completion of my literature review and interviews, Iwill complete a 30-40 page thesis discussing the use of blood quantum law.<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>APPENDIX QUESTIONS FOR INTERVIEW SUBJECTS</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
1) How would you define an Indian?<br>
2) How does this differ (if at all) from your definition of a member of your own tribe?<br>
3) What is your opinion of the federal blood quantum laws?<br>
4) How do you think federally-imposed criteria affects the American Indian community as a whole? <br>
How have you seen it affect individual people that you know personally? How has it affected members of your own tribe and/or community? <br>
5) How do you think federal blood quantum laws have affected tribal sovereignty?<br>
6) What do you think will be the long term affects of this policy on individual tribes? On the national American Indian community?<br>
7) How do you think federal blood quantum law has changed the way in which American Indians view each other? How has it affected the way people view themselves?<br>
8.) Do you think there is a legal basis for the federal government to impose such a criteria?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>For tribal leaders specifically:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
